Title: The Fifth Season (The Broken Earth, #1)
Author: N.K. Jemisin
My Review:
This is an extraordinary novel that delves into the intricacies of societal issues with a unique and enthralling narrative. At first, the story appears takes place in a dystopian world where civilization is on the brink of collapse due to constant natural disasters known as "Seasons." The society in this world is divided and oppressed, with a ruling class known as "Orogenes" who possess the power to control the earth's movements, but are treated as outcasts and enslaved. However, we eventually learn that the nearing apocalypse is caused, at least inadvertently, by the deeply unethical actions of the oppressors.

The author tackles themes such as oppression, inequality, and class division masterfully through the perspectives of three different female characters, each of whom are navigating their own struggles in this brutal world. The novel's focus on a feminine perspective is particularly noteworthy, as it adds a refreshing layer of depth and nuance to the exploration of these themes. The characters are complex and fully realized, making it easy for readers to connect with and understand their struggles.

Jemisin's writing is evocative and atmospheric, immersing readers in the world of the "Fifth Season" and making it easy to become emotionally invested in the story. The plot is expertly crafted, with twists and turns that keep the readers on the edge of their seats.

"The Fifth Season" is a thought-provoking and emotionally charged novel that is both unique and powerful in its exploration of societal issues in a unique fantasy setting.

Trigger warning, however, as there are rare but graphic depictions of sexual assault and violence.

I got about 45% through when it started going downhill.

Thinking of women as bitches and devising strategies to sleep with them, AND only wanting to buy a woman a drink while asking "what do I get?" is some early incel thinking.

Don't get me wrong, Feynman was a brilliant physicist and no one can doubt his contributions. Doesn't mean he was a good person. How disappointing to learn Feynman had such a lack of respect for half the population.

Title: On the Shortness of Life
Author: Seneca
My Review:
"Do as I say, not as I do" feels to apply to Seneca. His ideas are sound but feel disingenuous coming from him. It's very easy to write well about yourself, but that pales compared to what others say of you. Then, to go on and speak about how one should live their life, as if you're a paragon of stoic values, is shallow.

I'll stick to Epictetus and Aurelius.

Title: The Warded Man (The Demon Cycle, #1)
Author: Peter V. Brett
My Review:
I listened to the audiobook while driving around. An enjoyable read, with many prominent female characters of import. I am a little disappointed that the only culturally different people in the book are being cast as the enemy.

Mental health was an important theme in this book, surprisingly, and the characters had to face their demons (physically as well as metaphorically). Stoically getting on with life after turmoil is a common challenge amongst the main characters.

I must give this book a TW as there is a rather traumatic rape scene, which was unnecessary, but part of the character's arc of who is more evil: men or demons? Honestly it seems to be men, the demons are more like animals, the men should have some kind of moral compass.

Worth reading, the audiobook is easy to follow even with frequent stopping and starting while doing other tasks.

Title: Karamo: My Story of Embracing Purpose, Healing, and Hope
Author: Karamo Brown
My Review:
I'm always excited to read a book from an LGBTQ+ icon, as their experiences they share and respect they hold make them generally worth listening to.

However, my first contention: I totally disagree about not teaching kids about sex. It's important for kids to understand their bodies and their feelings (I know I first experienced sexual desires very young - at 7 - long before standard sex ed was taught in my country - 11). Sadly, we live in a world where kids are often exploited and abused by their elders. Equipping them with knowledge of respect, boundaries, consent, etc., provides a last resort bulwark in childhood as well as a foundation for adult life. It will also allow them to feel like they can ask questions to their parents, and let their guardians know if anyone has made them feel uncomfortable or broken boundaries. This kind of education is a powerful defence against grooming and should not be shied away from. We live in a scary world. Let's equip our children with the knowledge to defend against it.

Next, the God stuff. I've also read the Bible, and I'm sorry but it most certainly is homophobic. You said it yourself in your book Karamo: you read the Bible looking for and with the perspective of love. You didn't read it objectively, you cherry picked, which is exactly what you were preaching against. I'm not saying Christians are all homophobic, I'm saying the source text is. Please, be Christian and love much of the Bible, but there's nothing wrong with saying that some of it is problematic, and considering the number of times it's been translated, rewritten, modified, had bits added / removed, had a sequal that many dislike, and a prequel others dislike, it's impossible for it to be perfect - if it was, there would only be a single Christian religion!

I learned much about colorism from you, and I appreciate that. Being Scottish I barely knew any black people till my adult life and I only recently moved to the USA, so I am still ignorant about much of these issues. Thank you for taking the time to explain this.

I think Karamo speaks from a place of love and kindness, but often considers his own experiences to be applicable to everyone, and forms opinions in that respect.

I'm sure many people will enjoy this book. I am not one of them.

Title: The Name of the Wind (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #1)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review:
A masterful fantasy piece of writing. The only negative that must be mentioned is the lack of any female characters that are fully fleshed out. However, there was a great paragraph about the difficulties of being a working woman, the lack of opportunities and the dangers of a patriarchal society, which was insightful. I am told the next book improves with regard to representation of women, so I will continue on (without guilt).

So quotable, expertly written. I thought I was getting sick of fantasy books due to overuse of tropes but the mastery of world building, character development and the well considered hard magic system Rothfuss presents here has pleasantly surprised me.

I'm itching to move onto the next one. Thank you, Mr. Rothfuss.

My Review:
An incredibly important story that needed telling. There is much enthusing in other reviews and I feel I can't add further to those. I did feel like the writing itself was a little shaky at times and lacking flow, as if it could have done with more editing. Also, I listened to this rather than read it, and I didn't enjoy the narrator's amateur sounding recording: odd changes in volume, poor voice acting.

Overall well worth the read, and I hope this is read by many young LGBT+ peoples, as it may save a life.

Title: The Gentle Art of Verbal Self-Defense

My Review: I got through this book slowly over a few weeks as a sort of "I'm waiting on my tea to boil" kind of read. At the time of publishing (1980) this book referred to current science and concepts, and cultural norms, which aren't particularly relevant to the world of today. Additionally, I think this book really just explains what is innately known to many of us instinctively (e.g. the Satir modes). While useful to those who may not consciously understand the instinctive cues (such as responding in a computer Satir mode to someone throwing verbal-punches), I think most people wouldn't learn much from reading this.

Title: White Fragility: Why It’s So Hard for White People to Talk About Racism
Author: Robin DiAngelo
Additional Authors: Michael Eric Dyson, Manon Smits, Rob Kuitenbrouwer, Amy Landon
My Review:
Enlightening.

This handbook was a catalyst for self awareness in me. I'm certain that just last week I would have reacted defensively to being called racist, or even being told I said something problematic. I would have cried about how I am so very liberal, how I support BLM, etc., but I wouldn't have once tried to listen to the person trying to politely tell me that I said something offensive or upsetting.

I read, and was told by some, that this book goes "SJW levels" of liberalism. I admit I was wary going in - but that helped me pay careful attention to every word in this book. That only helped me accept the facts told.

I agree entirely with all the presented information in this book - though I think this book would only be read by people already willing to learn about racism. It doesn't reach the vast majority of people. So, I hope that us who read it, can instead become paragons of anti-white-fragility, provide examples of how to be open-minded to criticism and feedback from anyone about race.

If you are unsure about reading this book because you think it will be crackpot and "too woke", give it a shot and give it a thoroughly critical perusal. I think you will learn much about perspectives of your fellow humans, and in turn, allow you to critically analyze your own thoughts and actions regarding race.

Thank you, Robin DiAngelo.

I don't care if Dresden is an unreliable narrator, Butcher has made the decision to make (nearly) every woman a sex object. Particularly uncomfortable are the teenage girls that are "developing hips that weren't there before", or his best-friends daughter that he can't look at without thinking of sex - even when she has become gaunt and malnourished.

The rest is great. But every epic tale is littered with Dresden's (and therefore Butcher's) view on women.

Title: Goldenhand (Abhorsen, #5)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review:
Disappointed.

I was excited to learn there weeks more books after Abhorsen, though I see now that the author likely intended the books to be a trilogy, and had to force the last 2 books in. Book IV existed purely to set up a reason for book V to exist. As I said in my review of Clariel: sometimes over explaining can remove the magic of fantasy, and this was done here.

While I admit I guiltily enjoyed having Kibeth back, I still think the ending of Abhorsen was a good send off for the Disreputable Dog, and bringing her back to mention she'll attend Lirael's wedding... It's a bit sickly sweet and feels forced.

Title: Clariel (Abhorsen, #4)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review:
My favourite take-away from this book was having a main character who explicitly stated that she is not interested in men - nor in women. What a rarity that the protagonist (or, anti-hero perhaps) does not have romantic interests and is somewhat aromantic. Refreshing!

That being said, the knowledge-less power requirement for free magic enslavement in this book was rather disappointing. All you need is bloodline + will? It's a bit uninteresting. Chlorr of the Mask was, at least to me, a fascinating mix of ex-charter mage / abhorsen + necromancer. But in this book we learn she is only an abhorsen by blood (never trained), and is really more of a berserker, which is somehow free magic? Not a fan.

I'm going to continue onto Goldenhand and hope that this was a blip in the series that up until now I have thoroughly enjoyed. Sometimes mystery is more enjoyable than having everything explained, and I think this book removed some of the magic in this fantasy series.

Title: An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge
Author: Ambrose Bierce
My Review:
An interesting read. I guessed the ending early on, but it still came us a surprise due to the authors impressive writing skills and the hyper-realistic descriptions the character experiences. I suspect the cannon-shots were his heartbeat, and the final, painful depiction at the end was his neck snapping.

I didn't find myself upset at his death, I think the short length of this piece gave the readers little in the way of an emotional connection to the man. However, I did empathize with the thoughts of his wife in his final moments - that was rather sweet.

Title: Boys Don't Try? Rethinking Masculinity in Schools: Rethinking Masculinity in Schools
Author: Matt Pinkett
My Review:
I picked this up on a whim when there was an audible sale, because I fancied the title.

I didn't expect to find myself taking notes throughout. I learned of some fascinating concepts, such as the golem / Pygmalion effect. While I have always been an advocate for gender equality through activism focusing on each gender, I didn't know some of the statistics surround male suicide. I also didn't realize there was a swath of research being conducted on disruptive "laddish" behavior which my own years in school were hampered by.

Lastly, I didn't expect to be touched on a personal level, when Pinkett said (paraphrased): "Men will teach their boys that it's okay to cry, then never cry themselves". I never internalized that concept myself, and it, ironically, brought tears to my eyes. While I haven't been afraid of crying for some years, the concept of advocating for expressing emotions vs actually allowing oneself to experience them was eye-opening.

Thank you, Matt Pinkett, I'm glad you weren't satisfied with just inspiring students, but had to spread your wise words to readers globally.

Title: Salt, Fat, Acid, Heat: Mastering the Elements of Good Cooking
Author: Samin Nosrat
My Review:
A most educational book for a cooking novice like myself. I have only one criticism: many of the dishes described by the author are completely alien to me. Sharing stories of problems found in top French and Japanese restaurants, creating recipes I haven't tasted, smelled or even heard of do not aid in helping me with the basic and important elements in cooking.

That's a small criticism however - I learned much from this book. I had no idea about the benefits salting earlier in the cooking process (for so many foods but not all) vs later. I had a poor understanding of the Maillard reaction. I never really considered acid being such an important element, and really only considered vinegar, citrus and sour candies as acidic. Never before did I realize that salt was *so much more important* than other spices - I just assumed it was one of many, and was particularly favored in the small number of cultural foods I've explored. Turns out it's a key component in seemingly all countries and cultures.

As a non-meat eater, much of the content wasn't aimed at me, but I still found it interesting as an intellectual exercise on the physics of food science (applying heat, acids, etc.).

Well worth the read, especially with the short page count. I even tried making the homemade mayonnaise (which, it turns out, needs a neutral oil rather than olive oil, but it was still enjoyable!).

I'll now watch the Netflix series, as my friend pointed out is based on this book.

Title: The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn
Author: Mark Twain
Additional Authors: Guy Cardwell, E.W. Kemble, John Seelye, Walter Trier, Tom Wilson, William Little Hughes
My Review:
It's a classic for a reason.

This book really challenged my ability to consider a book in the era it was written. Never has the "n word" been voiced in mind so frequently as when reading this book, which is a cringe-inducing experience. But; I was surprised by Huckleberry Finn's ability to see his traveling companion as first a lesser being, but then in time as a friend and companion, and often considering how kind and intelligent the man is. I think, in the time written, this kind of character development may have resonated within the minds of people with societally-trained racist viewpoints and made them reconsider. At least, I hope it did.

I found myself laughing at ridiculous scenes and gullible youthful experiences of the protagonist, when I was expecting something more somber.

A strange consideration: when reading the speech of the slaves in this book, which is written in a (again, incredibly racist to modern standards) phonetic manner, I couldn't help but compare it to my childhood reading poetry and stories in Scots - because I found myself having to mentally voice the words as written to make sense of them - though obviously these were entirely different phonetically sounding words and tones, and entirely different contexts. Just an odd observation.

I grew to really enjoy Jim's character - such a sweet man, frequently weeping when he thinks he's lost Huck to his crazy adventures, and often thinking of his family back home. An overly trusting individual who lost his only fortune to the swindling church which was too happy to take his winnings.

Huckleberry Finn's gullible nature rubbed on me a little, and I was most glad when he realized that King and Duke were, infact, not a King nor a Duke. Then he goes and believes several of their on-the-spot synthetic tales of past deeds! A little infuriating but that is intended I'm sure - he's young and gullible, though surprisingly educated in the history of monarchies.

This is a good read - I wouldn't suggest it is a *must* read (like other classic American literature such as To Kill a Mockingbird which I recently reviewed). This novel certainly gives thoughtful insight into how societal / racial perspectives were, which in turn gives an interesting consideration as to how they developed into what they are today, and hopefully, where we can continue to improve in the future.

Title: Lirael (Abhorsen, #2)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review:
This is my second (maybe third?) read of Lirael, last read was some 15 years ago. While not quite as impactful as Sabriel, Lirael explores the old kingdom, the magic system, the ancient bloodlines and the creation of the world (or at least the old kingdom), through the characters Lirael, Sam, D.R. Dog and Mogget.

I previously gave this book a 4 star rating. While I enjoyed Lirael less than Sabriel: it is still an excellent read. The strong female lead (Lirael) is struggling with the meaning of her life - even nearly attempting suicide in the depths of her depression. A destiny is thrust upon her that she did not choose but she steps up to through a feeling of the threads of fate and realization that she won't merely be taking a new responsibility, but also a family. In a parallel and eventually coinciding story, Prince Sameth embarks on an adventure to save his school-friend, Nick, from the powers native to his kingdom. One character is attempting to embrace a role they do not want, while the other desperately clings for membership to a bloodline she will never be a true part of.

Lirael also successfully represents the struggles of a growing woman (from my limited viewpoint) avoiding the unwanted advances of male suitors. This is a difficult topic to approach, but Nix does so expertly - surprisingly. I personally would have assumed the author to be female to have such insights, but I am a man, so check reviews by women to see if I'm anywhere near correct.

Writing a sequel set decades after the original novel is difficult. Characters will have developed and matured, which needs to be shown, as well as the land and political climate etc., and the author did this expertly. The originally unsure Sabriel and guilt-ridden Touchstone have grown into defenders of the realm and true royal leaders.

Thanks for another excellent read, Garth Nix. On to Abhorsen.

Title: LIFEL1K3 (Lifelike, #1)
Author: Jay Kristoff
My Review:
I didn't give this book 1 star, though I was tempted to, because it is coherent and I didn't give up half-way through, tempted as I was.

I originally wrote out a long multi-paragraph review, but I'd rather condense it into bullet point format. I wish the author did the same with this book.

-Every character, other than the major plot twists, are two dimensional. For example, I know nothing about Ezekiel, except for the fact that he is pretty and his main story line. Does he have emotions, other than those required by his role as romantic interest?
-All of the plot, in it's entirety, is either invokes extreme emotions in the characters or humor. There is no in-between.
-Not all, but approximately 75% of all major plot points were predictable.
-The vast majority of dialogues are generic idioms and phrases, and author attempts to make up for this by introducing unique slang. The slang, however, feels forced and cringe-inducing.
-The violent moments with rockets and explosions seem to glance off the plot armor of all MCs, unless it makes a useful plot device.
-The main character is 1) extremely intelligent, 2) (un)naturally gifted fighter, 3) an engineering whiz, 4) a crack shot with a rifle, 5) extremely sociable so that humans and robots either fall in love with her or will die to protect her. A flaw or two would be nice. It was nice to see she wasn't gifted with some strange mutation (which was a cool fantasy element, by the way), but then she is also a freakin' lifelike at the end.
-The numbers in the title are unnecessary and irritating. Ok, this is a pet peeve and unimportant, but still.
-The ethics explored in the book, regarding slavery, bondage etc., are poorly explored and barely touched upon. In fact, the main characters are rather evil, but so are the villains in the story in a way due to the blood on their hands, but honestly I think the "villains" are more ethical than the MCs.
-I listened to the audiobook. The narrator is so slow and cartoonish which only increased my distaste for the story.
-Finally, I just didn't care about any of the characters. They have no depth. I just didn't care, and found myself frequently page-counting to see how long till this was over with. I don't understand the high rating this book has, because even if it's aimed at younger readers than myself, it has no depth to it. Most disappointed.

Title: Sabriel (Abhorsen,  #1)
Author: Garth Nix
My Review:
This was my third read, and first time reading as an adult. I was expecting my original 5 star rating to have been made in inexperienced and wide eyed ignorance, and for this to really be a 3* YA book.

Instead I was pleasantly surprised by a set of three dimensional characters, with a competent but flawed lead woman (I find often that women are portrayed poorly in fantasy and are archetypal Mary sues or "badass"). The magic system is unique, with the main character being effectively a necromancer bard, with a subclass in mage. Sex is mentioned only once, where the MC considers it an irritating distraction at best from her quest (why is this so uncommon?), and romance is tasteful and takes a backseat to the story - as it should when you're trying to save a nation or two.

The story is exciting, the world is fascinating and unique, the only flaw is a lack of variety in race and sexualities.

I still highly recommend this cornerstone of YA fantasy, and look forward to reading the rest in this series. Thank you Mr Nix.

Title: The Blind Watchmaker: Why the Evidence of Evolution Reveals a Universe Without Design
Author: Richard Dawkins
My Review:
As someone now working in genetics, reading the various books and listening to lectures by Dr Dawkins throughout my teen years constructed a good basis in my mind for more complex concepts.

This text is incredibly accessible for fairly complex ideas. I appreciate the candor employed by Dr Dawkins when discussing religion in scientific context: religion can exist as a personal belief without the broad claims on the origins of life (or the universe, for that matter).

Well written, with tidbits of humor and human-friendly tones not common in scientific writing (not that this is scientific writing, it is about science without being a scientific text).

Title: The Passage (The Passage, #1)
Author: Justin Cronin
My Review:
A few scattered thoughts:

It takes a great mind to compose a story composed of interesting characters with life-like traits and aspects, and to piece together various character arcs into a tapestry of such length and intricacy.

I feel that this book could easily have been made into three. I don't feel there was a need for so much of the story to be placed into a single tome.

The novelty in this book is lackluster. It's effectively a pre-then-post-apocalyptic tale of humanity, with zombies, who are actually kind of alive but kind of a swarm-like race, and have some kind of psychic link to the half-zombie-half-humans but also some humans, for some reason. The psychic elements are all rather hand-wavy and feel harshly fantasy in what is otherwise a storyline steeped in "has science gone too far?", except it's the military's fault, kind of.

I decided to read this because I really enjoy post-apocalyptic tales. I think they reflect what the author deems worth saving in humanity, which is beautiful. However, in this book, I feel that the author was too focused on considering how to mingle the various characters across time and space, and on their survival, rather than focusing on their reasons to survive (other than a couple of babies, which I understand is important, but tell us more reasons why humanity is worth saving other than reproduction and survival: ethics, philosophy, art, music, deep connections that aren't just for breeding.

This book, I would normally say, is worth reading. But, I read a fair bit, so I don't mind reading a book of this length for a 3/5 rating. But I imagine if I read 2-3 books a year and picked this up I'd be pretty disappointed, and I think that could be fixed merely by cutting this into 3 distinct novels.

In conclusion: it's well written overall, main concepts are not very novel and a bit hand-wavy, the characters are multi-dimensional but I never cared much about them throughout, and I feel this book misses the mark in the post-apocalyptic genre.

Title: The Great Gatsby
Author: F. Scott Fitzgerald
My Review:
I found the enigmatic character of Gatsby fascinating, but I felt that while his wealth is eventually explained, his character was still largely mystifying, and that lack of explanation left me feeling unsatisfied. Near the end of the book the main character (who is surprisingly unimportant in the story, so perhaps I should just call him the narrator and observer) begins contemplating on how the tale of Gatsby and the debacle represents America, and how beautiful the rugged land of America is. Title: The Story of China: A portrait of a civilisation and its people
Author: Michael Wood
My Review: I chose this as something I didn't think I would enjoy but would be important to read. I was half wrong - this was an absolute delight to read. Surprising depth in such breadth based overview of thousands of years of Chinese history. As someone whose only training in history was nationally based and only over 2 years at the ages of 11 & 12, this was highly accessible. The narrator, who is also the author, spoke with objective clarity - while still describing beautiful poetry, song, artwork and cultural masterpieces with passion. Unexpectedly still; Wood presented insight into the mindsets of Chinese women throughout the dynasties with compassion and a feminist heart. I will likely read this again, it is an oddly comforting, enlightening and most enjoyable read.

Title: Life of Pi
Author: Yann Martel
My Review:
Bit of a mind dump:

A fantastic story with a compelling main character. To have a story with only one perspective and really the only human for large chunks of the tale, shows the incredibly writing ability by Martel. Having seen the film first, I'm happy to say that it is a good representation of the book. While some aspects are missed, the cinematic beauty seen in the film captures the essence of what the character experiences: the majesty of God. Philosophical, introspective and exploring new avenues of thought regarding the role of religion and the worship of deities, this is an excellent book. I cannot truly relate to Pi and his perspective on religion, but reading it through his perspective is fascinating; it does not sway me. I wouldn't consider it a proof of God(s), but the proof of the reality-altering ability the mind appears to have in situations with levels of stress impossible to process.

Title: Murder on the Orient Express (Hercule Poirot, #9)
Author: Agatha Christie
My Review:
My first Christie book. What a tale. So well composed and thought out.

My only issue is with Poirot's perception (similar to the same issue with Moby Dick's "Ishmael") that all people from each nationality subgroup have individual character quirks. I don't believe that all Italians have a likeliness to stab nor that all Brits are cold and distant, and it's a rather illogical viewpoint for a detective.

But - I think that is a product of its time. This was originally published in 1934.

I heartily recommend this, in particular the audiobook version which is narrated by the actor for Poirot, David Suchet. He performs a wonderful array of accents and dialects, which really added to my enjoyment.

Title: Meditations
Author: Marcus Aurelius
Additional Authors: George Long, Diskin Clay, Martin Hammond, Duncan Steen, Edwin Ginn
My Review:
Emperor Aurelius provides wisdom from a life lived by few, and with wisdom not considered by most. His meditations are a must read for any budding stoic - or any opposing stoicism. While technically a short read, I spent many months reading this, slowly returning to read a few entries, then mulling over them in the intervening time.

Much of the wisdom within this text is comprised of repeated considerations for differing settings, so it can feel like you are re-reading the previous page, sometimes.

I wrote five pages or so of my favourite quotes I want to reconsider over time, here are a select few:

BOOK 3-4: Do not waste the remainder of thy life in thoughts about others, when thou dost not refer thy thoughts to some object of common utility. For thou losest the opportunity of doing something else when thou hast such thoughts as these.

BOOK 3-10: Throwing away then all things, hold to these only which are few; and besides bear in mind that every man lives only this present time, which is an indivisible point, and that all the rest of his life is either past or it is uncertain. Short then is the time which every man lives, and small the nook of the earth where he lives; and short too the longest posthumous fame, and even this only continued by a succession of poor human beings, who will very soon die, and who know not even themselves, much less him who died long ago.

(slightly different translation of 3-10, and a great standalone quote): Brief is man's life and small the nook of the earth where he lives.

BOOK 5-6: ...As a horse when he has run, a dog when he has tracked the game, a bee when it has made the honey, so a man when he has done a good act, does not call out for others to come and see, but he goes on to another act, as a vine goes on to produce again the grapes in season.

BOOK 8-4: Consider that men will do the same things nevertheless, even though thou shouldst burst with rage.

BOOK 8-42: It is not fit that I should give myself pain, for I have never intentionally given pain even to another.

BOOK 9-16: Not in passivity, but in activity lie the evil and the good of the rational social animal, just as his virtue and his vice lie not in passivity, but in activity.

Title: Little Women
Author: Louisa May Alcott
Additional Authors: Regina Barreca, Grzegorz Komerski, Marta Fihel
My Review:
"Try not to see works of the past through the lens of modern day".

I failed that.

This is so entrenched in idyllic Christian fantasies of nuclear family structures and women's firm place in the family, being sewing, producing many children, and petting down the men-folk when they come home from work, then returning quickly to look after the children.

I find myself being surprised and disgusted by norms of the time, and the incredulously sanitised perspective.

I read this because it's "A classic, and a masterpiece all should read.". Perhaps it once was - and my wife told me it is deemed feminist literature for it's time. Perhaps it should stay in the past, then, it truly comes off as toxic to me.

Admittedly; this has given me a view into the extreme difficulties women experienced in the past, and aided in my view of difficulties existing today for women. It is good to read, in the sense that Mein Kampf is good read, in order to set your moral compass into the opposite direction.

There is a clear lack of plot throughout this surprisingly lengthy piece. Again, my wife described this as a character study to me, and I agree - if we only study the characters through a puritan lens, on sins existing to be expunged and otherwise dull characteristics and traits.

I was also shocked at the chapter where Jo, a young aspiring writer, manages to sell some stories to a local publisher in New York, then confronted about it by a professor:

"There is a demand for whisky, but I think you and I do not care to sell it. If the respectable people knew what harm they did, they would not feel that the living was honest. They haf no right to put poison in the sugarplum, and let the small ones eat it. No, they should think a little, and sweep mud in the street before they do this thing."

The only description of her writings is that they are "sensational". This young author should completely give up her passion and career she is successfully pursuing because she's writing sensationalist pieces? What an awful moral to this story. Ironically, the professor thinks she should give up writing because there is a lack of morality in the writing.

"After all, why should a woman bother writing anything other than incredibly passive aggressive Christian fan fiction, when her place otherwise is birthing like a shackled farm cow?" - Louisa May Alcott, probably.

I don't think this book should be banned, removed from bookshelves in libraries or removed from school curriculums. I do think this should be read, I don't think this should be described as one of the "best pieces of literature of our time", as I've seen it referred to in critical reviews and advertised as such on book covers. I say this because I read this in the Audible series of "10 Masterpieces You Have to Read Before You Die".
